{"title_page": "John Thomas Simpson", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=John Thomas Simpson\n| birthname=John Thomas Simpson\n| image=\n| imagesize=150px\n| caption=\n| birth_date={{birth date|df=yes|1870|10|27}}\n| birth_place=[[Waverley, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date={{death date and age|1965|12|13|1870|10|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place=\n| spouse=Annie Clute<br />m. 3 November 1897<ref name=CPG32>{{cite book | title=Canadian Parliamentary Guide | first=A.L. | last=Normandin | year=1932 }}</ref>\n| residence=\n| riding=[[Simcoe North]]\n| predecessor=[[William Alves Boys]]\n| successor=[[Duncan Fletcher McCuaig]]\n| term_start=July 1930\n| term_end=October 1935\n| profession=farmer\n| party=[[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]]\n| footnotes=\n| religion=\n| website=\n|}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''John Thomas Simpson''' (27 October 1870 &ndash; 13 December 1965) was a [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]]. He was born in [[Waverley, Ontario]] and became a farmer and a municipal politician.\n\nSimpson attended schools in [[Simcoe County, Ontario|Simcoe County]], including [[Barrie]] Collegiate Institute. He served on the council of [[Simcoe County, Ontario|Simcoe County]] for 12 years, serving as councillor and reeve of [[Tiny, Ontario|Tiny Township]], becoming the county warden in 1913 and county clerk in 1922. In 1919, he was an unsuccessful candidate in the [[1919 Ontario general election|1919 Ontario election]].<ref name=CPG32 />\n\nHe was first elected to Parliament at the [[Simcoe North]] riding in the [[1930 Canadian federal election|1930 general election]]. After serving one term in the House of Commons, he was defeated by [[Duncan Fletcher McCuaig]] of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal party]] in the [[1935 Canadian federal election|1935 election]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=John Thomas Simpson |sopt=t}}\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=855}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simpson, John Thomas}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian farmers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942) MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n\n\n{{HistoricalConservative-Ontario-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox CanadianMP\n| name=John Thomas Simpson\n| birthname=John Thomas Simpson\n| image=\n| imagesize=150px\n| caption=\n| birth_date={{birth date|df=yes|1870|10|27}}\n| birth_place=[[Waverley, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date={{death date and age|1965|12|13|1870|10|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place=\n| spouse=Annie Clute<br />m. 3 November 1897<ref name=CPG32>{{cite book | title=Canadian Parliamentary Guide | first=A.L. | last=Normandin | year=1932 }}</ref>\n| residence=\n| riding=[[Simcoe North]]\n| predecessor=[[William Alves Boys]]\n| successor=[[Duncan Fletcher McCuaig]]\n| term_start=July 1930\n| term_end=October 1935\n| profession=farmer\n| party=[[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]]\n| footnotes=\n| religion=\n| website=\n|}}{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n'''John Thomas Simpson''' (27 October 1870 &ndash; 13 December 1965) was a [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]]. He was born in [[Waverley, Ontario]] and became a farmer and a municipal politician.\n\nSimpson attended schools in [[Simcoe County, Ontario|Simcoe County]], including [[Barrie]] Collegiate Institute. He served on the council of [[Simcoe County, Ontario|Simcoe County]] for 12 years, serving as councillor and reeve of [[Tiny, Ontario|Tiny Township]], becoming the county warden in 1913 and county clerk in 1922. In 1919, he was an unsuccessful candidate in the [[1919 Ontario general election|1919 Ontario election]].<ref name=CPG32 />\n\nHe was first elected to Parliament at the [[Simcoe North]] riding in the [[1930 Canadian federal election|1930 general election]]. After serving one term in the House of Commons, he was defeated by [[Duncan Fletcher McCuaig]] of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal party]] in the [[1935 Canadian federal election|1935 election]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=John Thomas Simpson |sopt=t}}\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=855}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simpson, John Thomas}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian farmers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942) MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n\n\n{{HistoricalConservative-Ontario-MP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Thomas_Simpson"}
